  "prompt": "U.S. Immigration: Can an H1-B visa be extended by future employers beyond 6 years based on an approved I-140 through the previous employer?",
  "response": "Yes, an H1-B visa can potentially be extended beyond the typical 6-year limit if the individual has an approved I-140 (Immigrant Petition for Alien Worker) from a previous employer. This is possible under certain circumstances:\n\n1. **Priority Date Retrogression**: If the individual's priority date is not current (i.e., there are delays in getting a visa number for their category), they may be eligible for one-year extensions beyond the six-year limit. \n\n2. **Pending Adjustment of Status or Immigrant Visa Application**: If the individual is waiting for their adjustment of status (Form I-485) or immigrant visa application to be approved because their priority date is not current, they can generally extend their H1-B visa in one-year increments until a decision is made.\n\n3. **Permanent Labor Certification Application (PERM) or I-140 Filed for at Least 365 Days**: If a PERM application or an I-140 petition was filed at least 365 days before the end of the individual's sixth year on an H1-B visa, extensions can be obtained in one-year increments.\n\nWhen changing employers, the new employer can file for an H1-B extension using the approved I-140 from the previous employer. However, the new employer will need to file a new H1-B petition for the individual, showing that the individual's sponsor is maintaining the intent to pursue the green card process. Appropriate documentation and adherence to USCIS regulations are critical in this process.\n\nThus, while the H1-B extension beyond six years is feasible under these provisions, it's recommended to consult with an immigration attorney for guidance and to ensure compliance with all relevant documentation and procedures.",
